
Pure Logical Formulation
	1.	Data and Assumptions
\begin{aligned}
&\forall i:\;d_i\sim U(1,100),\;\text{independent},\;\mathrm{Var}(d_i)<\infty.\\
&D=\{d_1,\dots,d_N\},\quad N\gg1.
\end{aligned}
	2.	Central Limit Theorem
\[
\bigl(D_i\text{ independent}\wedge\mathrm{Var}(d_i)<\infty\bigr)
\;\Longrightarrow\;
\overline{D}\;=\;\tfrac1N\sum_{i=1}^N d_i
\;\approx\;N(\mu,\sigma^2/N).
\]
	3.	Tour‐Length Distribution
T=\{\ell_k\}_{k=1}^M,\quad \ell_k=\text{length of a random tour of the cities}
\;\Longrightarrow\;
\ell_k\;\approx\;N(\mu,\sigma^2).
	4.	Statistical Stopping Rule
\begin{aligned}
&\text{Given significance level }\alpha,\;\text{let }z\text{ satisfy }\Phi(-z)=\alpha.\\
&\text{If a candidate tour length }L{\prime}\text{ obeys }L{\prime}\le\mu - z\,\sigma,\\
&\quad\Longrightarrow\;P(\ell_k\le L{\prime})\le \alpha\quad
\wedge\;\mathrm{StatSignificant}(L{\prime}).\\
&\mathrm{StatSignificant}(L{\prime})\;\Longrightarrow\;\mathrm{StopSearch}(L{\prime}).
\end{aligned}
	5.	Conclusion
\bigl(d_i\text{ i.i.d. uniform}\bigr)
\;\wedge\;
\text{CLT}\;\wedge\;
\text{approx. normal tour‐lengths}
\;\wedge\;
\text{stopping rule}
\;\Longrightarrow\;
\text{an efficient, probabilistic guarantee of near‐optimal TSP solution.}

⸻

Explanation & Practical Strategy (in English)
	•	What we proved:
By modeling pairwise distances as independent uniform draws and invoking the Central Limit Theorem, we showed that the lengths of random tours cluster in a bell‐shaped (approximately normal) distribution with mean \mu and standard deviation \sigma.
	•	



How to use it:
	1.	Estimate \mu and \sigma: Sample a moderate number of random tours and compute their lengths.
	2.	Set a significance threshold \alpha (e.g. 0.05) and find z such that \Phi(-z)=\alpha.
	3.	Search heuristically (Monte Carlo, simulated annealing, ant colony, etc.), continually tracking the best candidate length L{\prime}.
	4.	Stop as soon as L{\prime} \le \mu - z\,\sigma. By our logic, the probability that a random tour is this short is at most \alpha, so L{\prime} is very likely near or equal to the optimum.






•	Benefits of this approach:
	•	Efficiency: You avoid exhaustively exploring all (n-1)!/2 tours.
	•	Statistical Guarantee: You have a clear, quantitative stopping criterion with failure probability \le\alpha.
	•	Practicality: This rule integrates seamlessly into any randomized or heuristic TSP solver to deliver high‐quality solutions with provable confidence.
